org.mundo.rt
Class TypedMap

java.lang.Object
  org.mundo.rt.TypedContainer
      org.mundo.rt.TypedMap
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Cloneable, java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object>, IActivate, ICopy
public final class TypedMap
extends TypedContainer
implements IActivate, java.lang.Cloneable, ICopy, java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object>

A TypedMap holds an object tree either in an active or passive form and has operations to transform from one form to the other. Active object trees hold arbitrary object types. Because the actual objects are instantiated, the code associated with these objects is also loaded and runnable. Passive object trees only hold the state of objects which is represented by a number of base types, an array and a map type as listed in the table below.

ScalarNumberByte
TypedContainer.UnsignedByte
Short
TypedContainer.UnsignedShort
Integer
TypedContainer.UnsignedInteger
Long
TypedContainer.UnsignedLong
Float
Double
Boolean
Character
String
GUID
ArrayTypedArray
HashTypedMap
otherJavaXDR

It is not possible to derive from TypedMap (for good reasons). If you need to add functionality or you want to filter active objects, you have to use ActiveMap.

It has been heavily discussed in the past if this class should be final or not. A non-final TypedMap would have the following problems:

  • TypedMap is used to hold a predefined set of basic types. This set is not extensible. Introducing new types would break things in lower layers, like serializers, and compatibility with other language versions of MundoCore.
  • Activate, passivate, and clone are used by the framework and must be implemented properly. TypedMap is special in the sense that any object can be passivated into a TypedMap, and a TypedMap can be activated into any defined object. The activeClassName member defines if a TypedMap is just cloned during activation or converted into an active object. A class deriving from TypedMap must take care of all these aspects as well.
  • A class derived from TypedMap must not use the Tiger build model. TypedMap uses the activation model based on IActivate, and the Tiger build model uses activation based on Metaclasses. These two models cannot be mixed in the same inheritance tree.

CLDC: Floating point types and JavaXDR are not available in this configuration.

Author:
Erwin Aitenbichler

java.lang.ClassCastException - if the specified key is not mapped to a Character. This exception can only happen in case of a type mismatch, i.e. the specified key has not previously been mapped by the putChar method.

toString

public java.lang.String toString()
Returns a string representation of this map. The string representation consists of a list of key-value mappings in the order returned by the map's entrySet view's iterator, enclosed in braces ("{}"). The active class name is printed, if it is set, followed by a colon (":"). Adjacent mappings are separated by the characters ", " (comma and space). Each key-value mapping is rendered as the key followed by an equals sign ("=") followed by the associated value.

Overrides:
toString in class java.lang.Object
See Also:
Object.toString()

containsValue

public boolean containsValue(java.lang.Object value)
Returns true if this map maps one or more keys to this value. More formally, returns true if and only if this map contains at least one mapping to a value v such that (value==null ? v==null : value.equals(v)). This operation will probably require time linear in the map size for most implementations of map.

Specified by:

See Also:
Map.containsValue(Object)

entrySet

public java.util.Set<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object>> entrySet()
Returns a set view of the mappings contained in this map. Each element in this set is a Map.Entry. The set is backed by the map, so changes to the map are reflected in the set, and vice-versa. (If the map is modified while an iteration over the set is in progress, the results of the iteration are undefined.) The set supports element removal, which removes the corresponding entry from the map, via the Iterator.remove, Set.remove, removeAll, retainAll and clear operations. It does not support the add or addAll operations.

Specified by:
entrySet in interface java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object>
See Also:
Map.entrySet()

Returns the value to which this map maps the specified key. Returns null if the map contains no mapping for this key.
